ABUJA – The All Progressives Congress (APC) has mourned the demise of Chief Ernest Shonekan, leader of the Interim National Government (ING) set up after the annulment of the June 12, 1993 election. John James Akpanudee­dehe, secretary to APC Care­taker Extraordinary Conven­tion Planning Committee (CECPC) in a statement de­scribed the late Head of In­terim National Government (ING) as a committed nation­alist whose intervention in the polity “doused tension at the time, when Nigeria was at crossroads, and almost on the brink of conflict.” The message reads: “I re­ceived with a deep sense of sadness, news of the passing of a one-time Head of the Ni­gerian Interim National Gov­ernment (ING); the Abese of Egbaland; and my late father’s colleague, H.E. Chief (Dr.) Er­nest Shonekan, GCFR, CBE. NYSC Gets Commendation On Innovative Service Delivery Absence of Governing Council Hindering AAU Progress, ASUU… “Late Chief Shonekan who passed on at 85, was Head of the Nigerian government that succeeded General Ibrahim Babangida’s regime on Au­gust 26, 1993, but was ousted by the regime of late General Sani Abacha, on November 17, 1993.